Freedom to Marry's Roadmap to Victory outlines the three ways the organization plans to end the exclusion of same-sex couples from marriage. 

Win More States: Currently only six states (Massachusetts, Connecticut, Iowa, Vermont, New Hampshire, and New York) and the District of Columbia recognize marriage equality for same-sex couples, while seven states (Washington, Oregon, California, Nevada, Illinois, and New Jersey) allow civil unions or domestic partnerships. The more states that over turn anti-gay constitutional amendments, the greater the momentum towards countrywide acceptance of same-sex marriage.&nbsp;
Grow The Majority For Marriage: According to a 2010 Associated Press poll, 52% of Americans believe that the government should recognize marriages between same-sex couples, and 58% think that same-sex couples should receive the same government benefits as married couples. Freedom to Marry works to grow this majority of equality through public education and dialogue, believing that an increase in the number of Americans who support the same rights for all couples is the biggest challenge against marriage inequality.&nbsp;
End Federal Marriage Discrimination: Freedom to Marry's ultimate goal is the repeal of the "Defense of Marriage Act" by creating the right climate for ongoing federal litigation challenging DOMA with a growing majority of Americans supporting marriage equality and additional states extending marriage rights to same-sex couples.      ﻿
